VALUES ('fdc7bd81-a2d6-45ff-8021-6d20082515cf', 'Which finding, if true, would most directly support Dr. Morales''s hypothesis?', 'Urban sociologist Dr. Morales hypothesized that community gardens logging at least $15$ weekly volunteer hours produce larger harvests than gardens with lighter volunteer turnout, but only when cultivation methods are held constant across sites. In gardens where managers changed fertilizer regimes mid-season, Morales predicted volunteer hours alone would not reliably predict harvest size. She tracked 3 gardens through one growing season, recording weekly labor and total vegetable yield in pounds. The authors caution that replication remains necessary before treating the finding as settled.', 'passage', '[{"id":"A","text":"Among gardens with fixed cultivation methods, low-hour sites outproduced high-hour sites by $123$ pounds on average, a true floor value that does not compare treatments as the stem requires., yet the.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"[Inverse Support] Low-hour gardens outproducing high-hour sites contradicts the predicted labor effect."},{"id":"B","text":"Among gardens with fixed cultivation methods, sites averaging at least $15$ volunteer hours per week harvested $803$ pounds, whereas sites averaging fewer than $10$ hours harvested $393$ pounds.","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Compares high- and low-hour gardens under fixed cultivation, directly testing the labor threshold claim."},{"id":"C","text":"Every garden in the study harvested more than $353$ pounds regardless of volunteer hours or fertilizer changes, a figure accurate in isolation but not linked to the researchers'' stated conclusion., describing one.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"[Unconditional Support Decoy] Harvest floors without hour comparisons do not test the hypothesis."},{"id":"D","text":"Gardens that switched fertilizer regimes mid-season showed higher soil nitrogen readings than gardens with fixed regimes, independent of volunteer hours, describing one row only rather than the cross-row contrast the claim.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"[Irrelevant Variable] Soil nitrogen under fertilizer changes is outside the volunteer-hour prediction."}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Step 1 — State the claim
Focus on {{yellow:methods}} in the passage. The textual evidence item asks you to state the claim before comparing choices.

Step 2 — Find supporting language
Compare each option against explicit textual evidence. On easy items, correct answers usually restate the passage faithfully without absolute words the text does not support.

Step 3 — Select the best evidence
Choice B is correct: Among gardens with fixed cultivation methods, sites averaging at least $15$ volunteer hours per week harvested $803$ pounds, whereas sites averaging fewer than ….

Distractor analysis:
- A: [Unconditional Support Decoy] [Inverse Support] Low-hour gardens outproducing high-hour sites contradicts the predicted labor effect.
- C: [Irrelevant Variable] [Unconditional Support Decoy] Harvest floors without hour comparisons do not test the hypothesis.
- D: [Inverse Support] [Irrelevant Variable] Soil nitrogen under fertilizer changes is outside the volunteer-hour prediction.', NULL, 'Information and Ideas', 'Command of Evidence', 'reading_writing', 'information', 'COE', NULL, 'easy', false, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"rw_subtype":"textual_evidence","dsat_blueprint_v1":true,"rw_format":"hypothesis_support","generator":"regenerate-english-fresh.mjs","master_manual_section":"5","english_rw_regen_v2":true,"regen_agent":"coe-master","regen_seed_offset":100000,"explanation_v2":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
