VALUES ('4bc1a344-ddde-4473-9651-3516a676e9c9', 'Which finding, if true, would most directly support Dr. Wei''s hypothesis?', 'Environmental chemist Dr. Lin Wei hypothesized that a synthetic pesticide degrades rapidly due to microbial activity stimulated by warm temperatures, but only in shallow surface sediments where dissolved oxygen is abundant. In deep sediments, where anaerobic conditions prevail, Dr. Wei claimed that seasonal temperature changes have no statistically significant effect on pesticide concentration. Her sediment cores were collected from 8 wetland sites and analyzed across four seasons under controlled laboratory extraction protocols. The authors caution that replication remains necessary before treating the finding as settled.', 'passage', '[{"id":"A","text":"Dissolved oxygen levels in surface sediments averaged $6.1\\text{ mg/L}$ across seasons, while deep sediments averaged $1.4\\text{ mg/L}$, confirming the anaerobic profile described in the passage, describing one row only rather than the cross-row contrast the claim requires., which restates table values, reporting, a true, yet the.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"[Irrelevant Variable] Oxygen measurements do not test seasonal pesticide concentration change."},{"id":"B","text":"Deep sediment pesticide concentrations dropped by $22\\%$ between spring and summer, while surface concentrations remained stable across the same interval, which restates table values without connecting them to the hypothesis in the passage., but the statement fails to contrast the groups named in the passage''s central.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"[Inverse Support] Deep-sediment decline with surface stability contradicts the predicted depth-specific pattern."},{"id":"C","text":"Pesticide concentrations in surface sediments fell from $11.4\\text{ }\\mu\\text{g/L}$ in spring to $4.2\\text{ }\\mu\\text{g/L}$ in summer, whereas concentrations in deep sediments remained virtually unchanged between spring ($24.8\\text{ }\\mu\\text{g/L}$) and summer ($24.5\\text{ }\\mu\\text{g/L}$).","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Supports both conditional parts: sharp summer decline in surface sediments and stability in deep sediments."},{"id":"D","text":"Across all three sediment depths, pesticide concentrations reached their lowest levels during summer, with deep sediments recording $24.5\\text{ }\\mu\\text{g/L}$ and surface sediments recording $4.2\\text{ }\\mu\\text{g/L}$, accurate yet non-diagnostic because it ignores the variable the researchers emphasize., reporting a ranking, a, a.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"[Unconditional Support Decoy] Claims summer minima at every depth, overstating temperature sensitivity in deep anaerobic layers."}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Step 1 — State the claim
