VALUES ('77251db1-6e3b-4a44-9cf8-b0bdef6e8d59', 'Which finding, if true, would most directly support Dr. Morales''s hypothesis?', 'Urban sociologist Dr. Morales hypothesized that community gardens logging at least $15$ weekly volunteer hours produce larger harvests than gardens with lighter volunteer turnout, but only when cultivation methods are held constant across sites. In gardens where managers changed fertilizer regimes mid-season, Morales predicted volunteer hours alone would not reliably predict harvest size. She tracked 5 gardens through one growing season, recording weekly labor and total vegetable yield in pounds. The authors caution that replication remains necessary before treating the finding as settled.', 'passage', '[{"id":"A","text":"Every garden in the study harvested more than $369$ pounds regardless of volunteer hours or fertilizer changes, a true floor value that does not compare treatments as the stem requires., yet the.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"[Unconditional Support Decoy] Harvest floors without hour comparisons do not test the hypothesis."},{"id":"B","text":"Gardens that switched fertilizer regimes mid-season showed higher soil nitrogen readings than gardens with fixed regimes, independent of volunteer hours, yet the comparison omits the pairing required to test the.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"[Irrelevant Variable] Soil nitrogen under fertilizer changes is outside the volunteer-hour prediction."},{"id":"C","text":"Among gardens with fixed cultivation methods, low-hour sites outproduced high-hour sites by $149$ pounds on average, a figure accurate in isolation but not linked to the researchers'' stated conclusion., describing one row.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"[Inverse Support] Low-hour gardens outproducing high-hour sites contradicts the predicted labor effect."},{"id":"D","text":"Among gardens with fixed cultivation methods, sites averaging at least $15$ volunteer hours per week harvested $819$ pounds, whereas sites averaging fewer than $10$ hours harvested $419$ pounds.","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Compares high- and low-hour gardens under fixed cultivation, directly testing the labor threshold claim."}]'::jsonb, 'D', 'Step 1 — State the claim
Focus on {{yellow:methods}} in the passage. The textual evidence item asks you to state the claim before comparing choices.

Step 2 — Find supporting language
Compare each option against explicit textual evidence. On easy items, correct answers usually restate the passage faithfully without absolute words the text does not support.

Step 3 — Select the best evidence
Choice D is correct: Among gardens with fixed cultivation methods, sites averaging at least $15$ volunteer hours per week harvested $819$ pounds, whereas sites averaging fewer than ….

Distractor analysis:
- A: [Unconditional Support Decoy] Harvest floors without hour comparisons do not test the hypothesis.
- B: [Irrelevant Variable] Soil nitrogen under fertilizer changes is outside the volunteer-hour prediction.
- C: [Inverse Support] Low-hour gardens outproducing high-hour sites contradicts the predicted labor effect.', NULL, 'Information and Ideas', 'Command of Evidence', 'reading_writing', 'information', 'COE', NULL, 'easy', false, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"rw_subtype":"textual_evidence","dsat_blueprint_v1":true,"rw_format":"hypothesis_support","generator":"regenerate-english-fresh.mjs","master_manual_section":"5","english_rw_regen_v2":true,"regen_agent":"coe-master","regen_seed_offset":100000,"explanation_v2":true}'::jsonb, now(), now());
